value.0: "When Sir Becket belittled me, you were kind. I suppose you might not be asking about me for simple amusement. Very well, what would you like to know?"
"Did you have any other questions then?"
"No. I have no interest in love. I have seen and heard what comes to those who love."
"I fear that something bad might happen and I would end up serving justice on the one I loved. Such a thing could drive even a paladin to do horrible things."
"But that doesn't matter. I have such a busy life; I would have no time to devote to a husband anyways. Was there anything else?"
"When I was thirteen years old I had a friend named Jimmy. The two of us were very close and we would often get into trouble."
"Being poor, we would steal the things we wanted, such as sweets, ale and sometimes weapons from the smith. Usually we got away with our petty crimes."
"One day we decided to break into the house of a nobleman. We thought that he could hardly miss a few trinkets, with all that he owned. We were wrong."
"I just wish we would have been caught by someone else. Someone with a sense of mercy."

Comment.value: mark that pc knows about Jimmy

value.0: "The noble decided to administer justice himself, so he had one of his guards chop off Jimmy's hand. I was supposed to be next, except that at the last minute, Jimmy moved and the swordsman overreacted."
"Instead of removing his hand, the guard almost removed Jimmy's head. It was... I can't even talk about it."
"The noble was caught unprepared and was covered in the spray of Jimmy's blood. He had his guards take Jimmy's body to the Banner."
"The guards told the Banner that we had broken into the house, but when caught, Jimmy had pulled a weapon and threatened them with it."
"It was a lie, but no one would take the word of a thirteen-year-old thief over a rich and powerful noble."
"From then on I decided to pursue justice. I do not allow evil to go unpunished, but I make sure that I investigate every case as best I can. That is how I became a paladin."
"My entire life has been this keep. My parents were adventurers who came here a long time ago. They were both killed while exploring some of the deeper caves."
"I, like so many others in this land, was raised an orphan. The woman who raised me was a servant in the keep, her husband a groom."
"It has been a good life and I have few complaints. There are days I have dreamed of living a more adventurous life, but there is security here in the keep."
"Despite the amount of energy I have spent trying to drive such activities out of our lands, assassinations do occur, though rarely."
"I could guess who would do such a thing, but I have no evidence to prove it. Even this note is nothing."

value.0: "There are nine guildmasters who will cast their votes to decide who becomes the Lady or Lord of the Keep. The winner must have a clear majority. It isn't really that difficult a concept."
As you arrive, you see the Hand, Enivid, speaking with a man in priestly raiment.
"We have driven off the last of them. Do you think they will come again?"
"If their leader still lives, there are enough of them to regroup and return. Hopefully Yenna has taken care of that for us for, if not, it will only be a matter of time before they return."
"We have killed enough of them that it should give them pause. We should have a little time to recuperate. I just hope it is enough."
"If Pharos, Lord of Battles, judges us worthy, we shall continue. I wish the Banner yet lived."
"So do I, Dynschall, so do I. The keep needs a strong leader. Perhaps it is time I assumed the role of Banner, though the timing strikes fear into my very soul."
"My Lady, we are all saddened by the Banner's death, but might I introduce someone who brings hope?"
"We welcome any relief in this war, even if it is just a temporary respite. Tell us, Dylan, who is this one who stands before us?"
"I neither need nor appreciate flattery, sir."
"I am pleased to introduce <Master/Mistress> <FirstName>. A hero who has come to our lands at great peril to <him/her>self."
"The <man/woman> who broke through the battle lines and distracted the Masked Man long enough for Yenna to see to his destruction. If it weren't for this hero, all Cyan would surely have been lost!"
Dylan blushes and says nothing more.
Enivid eyes you warily. "It was good of you to come to our aid. As the Hand, an officer of the Keep of Cyan, I welcome you."
"So, Enivid, once more your incompetence has led to the death of more of our valiant defenders. With the Banner dead, we are in sore need of a true ruler."
"As I was saying, Sir Becket, I am the highest ranking officer here in the keep."
"My dear, do you really think that the people would settle for a poor orphan as the Lord of the Keep?"
"Lord? I did not think we were..."
"That is alright, my dear, no one expects you to actually think."
Enivid gives you a cold stare, while Sir Becket nods and smiles.
"Everyone knows that our late Banner was next in line to become Lord, yet he refused the honor. Now that he is gone, it is time we truly had a new Lord of the Keep."
"And I suppose you think you should be our mighty ruler?"
"Well, I am part of the nobility and I am soon to marry the highest ranked noble in our lands, Lady Ellysia, so I think I deserve to be considered."
"The nobles have always ruled here!"
"Not anymore! This is something the guild leaders have discussed, and with the exception of your betrothed, we agreed that the guilds would choose the next Lord or Lady of the Keep."
"That would be fair. Then even the nobles will have a say in it."
"I see nothing fair about it. The Banner was... well, I should not speak ill of the dead, but the guilds should never have been allowed to gain so much power."
"There are nine guilds in the city, including one for the nobles. The guildmasters make most of the decisions that affect the daily operations of the keep."
"So Enivid and Sir Becket shall make their appeals before the guildmasters and then they will vote to decide the leader."
"The keep won't truly be safe until we have a strong leader who can destroy the invaders, not just drive them off or hide behind these walls!"
"Why are we limited to those two as our only choices? What if we want a real hero as our <Lord/Lady>?"
"And where precisely are we going to find a real hero?"
"This young <man/woman> saved our lives!"
"Right place, right time, but that does not make <him/her> a hero!"
Your weapon speaks in your mind. "This is the moment. Though none realize it, I have been at work in the keep to prepare people for this election."
"They will feel more comfortable around you than they would have. You will have to work to gain votes, but they will be open to voting for you once you do something for them."
"Besides, we know nothing about <him/her>. <FirstName> might not even be interested in staying here at our keep."
As the words start to leave your mouth, the voice of your weapon echoes in your head. "You must pursue this opportunity. It is for this that you have been allowed to live."
The weapon continues as the others wait for you to speak. "Whatever your desire: power, prestige, piety, vengeance or unprecedented wealth, this is your only path to reaching it."
"As <FirstName> has never met the guildmasters and is not well known in the keep, we will postpone the guild vote for several days."

value.0: "<FirstName>, you deserve a reward for your efforts in helping the keep. I would like you to take this... it's my old crossbow and bolts. Both are magical, so you can either sell them or use them."
"I need to arrange for funeral rites for the Banner. Then I suppose I will have to do my best to counteract all the deception Sir Becket will be trying, not to mention my duties as the Hand."
"Alias is a local scout. She, like me, is an orphan. You will find many of the people here at the keep have lost loved ones."
"Ah, here comes Alias now. She can answer any questions you might have. I shall be going now. May the best person win."
"Sir Becket is a serpent, waiting in the grass to strike at his opponents. He has no honor and his lack of scruples will give him some advantage in manipulating the vote."
"That is the only chance he has to win this election. I will do my best to stop him."
"That is up to you. If you are serious about the election, you will need to meet with as many guildmasters as possible and see if you can win any votes."
"You might also want to go out of the keep and prove you really are a hero. The Masked Man's armies have scattered but people in the keep would rest easier knowing they are destroyed for good."
"I don't really think you stand much of a chance, but I guess you think you have something I don't have."
"Very well, but be quick. I must get everything in order so I can keep an eye on Sir Becket and his schemes."
"I have been the Hand here for a fairly long time. My reputation as a good military leader is already known."

"A few guilds might vote for that deceiver, Sir Becket, but not enough for him to win. He will have to try something nefarious, and I am going to spend my time making sure he doesn't have that chance."
"You might have impressed some of the commoners, like that old gossip Momma Dane, but impressing a guildmaster is entirely different. They don't know you. You have never done anything for them."
"You would have to do something very impressive for each of them and you don't have the time for that, not before the election. I don't need time: I can win on my own merit."
"Those are the titles of the highest ranking officers, below the lord. The Banner is the person who promotes the lord's justice and sees to the everyday operations of the keep."
"The Hand upholds the Banner, as the Captain of the guards. The Hand is in charge of the military and defense of the keep."
"No, we could have a Lady of the Keep. I intend to be a contender. I have earned the right to at least try."
